---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";


export const meta = {
  title: 'Freelance Contract Template Guide',
  description: 'Master the essentials of freelance contracts. Learn key clauses, red flags, tools, and how to protect yourself on every gig.',
  category: 'guide',
};

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Do I really need a contract if I am working with a friend?",
    a: "Yes. Even when working with friends, a contract clarifies expectations, scopes the project, and protects your relationship by avoiding misunderstandings about money or deliverables."
  },
  {
    q: "What is a kill fee?",
    a: "A kill fee is a clause in your contract that guarantees you a percentage of the total project fee if the client decides to cancel the project before completion. It compensates you for the time and resources you have already committed."
  },
  {
    q: "Should I charge hourly or by milestone?",
    a: "Milestone-based pricing is generally better for project work because it focuses on the value delivered rather than the time spent. Hourly billing is better for ongoing maintenance or tasks where the scope is undefined."
  },
  {
    q: "When should I involve a lawyer in reviewing a contract?",
    a: "Consider involving a lawyer if the contract is for a high-value project, involves complex intellectual property transfers, includes a stringent non-compete clause, or if you are working with an international enterprise where jurisdiction laws apply."
  },
  {
    q: "What are some good tools for sending freelance contracts?",
    a: "Popular and reliable tools for sending, signing, and managing freelance contracts include HelloSign (Dropbox Sign), PandaDoc, and AND CO (Fiverr Workspace). They offer legally binding e-signatures and templates."
  }
];

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": f.q,
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": f.a
      }
    }))
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="getthebag"
  title="Freelance Contract Template Guide"
  description="Master the essentials of freelance contracts. Learn key clauses, red flags, tools, and how to protect yourself on every gig."
  canonical="https://getthebag.photonbuilder.com/freelance-contract-guide"
  schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Freelance Contract Template Guide</h1>
      <p>Master the essentials of freelance contracts, protect your business, and ensure you get paid on time, every time.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Why You Need a Contract (Even for Friends)</h2>
      <p>A contract is not just a legal document; it is a communication tool. It sets clear boundaries, defines the scope of work, and establishes payment expectations. Even if you are working for a close friend or family member, a contract prevents misunderstandings that could damage the relationship.</p>

      <h2>Key Clauses Every Contract Needs</h2>
      <p>To protect yourself and your business, ensure your contract includes these essential clauses:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Scope of Work:</strong> Clearly define exactly what you will deliver, how many revisions are included, and what is considered out of scope.</li>
        <li><strong>Payment Terms:</strong> Detail how much you will be paid, when payments are due (e.g., net 30, upon completion), and outline late payment penalties.</li>
        <li><strong>Revision Limits:</strong> Specify the number of revision rounds included in the base fee to prevent endless scope creep.</li>
        <li><strong>Kill Fee:</strong> A percentage of the project fee guaranteed to you if the client cancels the project prematurely.</li>
        <li><strong>IP Ownership:</strong> Clarify who owns the intellectual property once the project is finished. Usually, ownership transfers to the client upon full payment.</li>
        <li><strong>Confidentiality:</strong> An NDA (Non-Disclosure Agreement) clause to protect the client's sensitive information.</li>
        <li><strong>Non-Compete:</strong> Be cautious with these. If included, ensure it does not unreasonably restrict your ability to work with other clients in your industry.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Late Payment Penalties</h2>
      <p>Always include a clause detailing late payment penalties. Common practices include charging a percentage (e.g., 2-5%) of the outstanding invoice amount per month past the due date. This incentivizes clients to pay promptly.</p>

      <h2>Milestone-Based vs. Hourly Contracts</h2>
      <p>For discrete projects, milestone-based contracts often work best. They tie payments to specific deliverables (e.g., 50% upfront, 25% after the first draft, 25% upon completion), providing steady cash flow. Hourly contracts are better suited for ongoing, open-ended work or maintenance tasks where the total scope is unpredictable.</p>

      <h2>Contract Templates by Industry</h2>
      <p>Different industries require different specific clauses. A design contract needs strict IP and revision clauses. A writing contract might need to address bylines and plagiarism. A development contract should detail bug-fixing periods and server access rights. Always tailor your baseline template to your specific field.</p>

      <h2>Tools for Managing Contracts</h2>
      <p>Streamline your workflow with tools like HelloSign, PandaDoc, or AND CO. These platforms offer legally binding e-signatures, professional templates, and automated tracking for when clients view and sign the documents.</p>

      <h2>Red Flag Client Behaviors</h2>
      <p>Be wary of clients who refuse to sign a contract, balk at upfront deposits, consistently ask for "just one more quick change" (scope creep), or are overly vague about their goals. A contract helps weed out problematic clients early on.</p>

      <h2>When to Involve a Lawyer</h2>
      <p>While standard templates work for many freelancers, you should consult a lawyer for high-stakes projects, complex enterprise agreements, international contracts (where jurisdiction laws apply), or if you are navigating a tricky non-compete clause.</p>

      <h2>International Contracts</h2>
      <p>When working across borders, explicitly state which country or state's laws govern the contract (jurisdiction). Also, agree on the currency for payment and how exchange rates or international transfer fees will be handled.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div>
        {faqs.map(f => (
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>{f.q}</h3>
            <p>{f.a}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="related-tools" style="margin-top:3rem;padding-top:2rem;border-top:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);">
    <h2 style="font-size:1.2rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">🔗 Related Tools</h2>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(280px,1fr));gap:1rem;">
      <a href="https://firemaths.info/how-to-read-a-lease" style="display:block;background:rgba(255,255,255,0.03);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);border-radius:10px;padding:1.25rem;text-decoration:none;color:inherit;transition:border-color 0.2s,transform 0.2s;" onmouseover="this.style.borderColor='rgba(255,255,255,0.2)';this.style.transform='translateY(-2px)'" onmouseout="this.style.borderColor='rgba(255,255,255,0.08)';this.style.transform='none'">
        <strong style="font-size:0.95rem;">How to Read a Lease: Clauses, Rights, and Red Flags</strong>
        <p style="opacity:0.6;font-size:0.83rem;margin:0.4rem 0 0;line-height:1.4;">Understand your rental agreement before you sign. We cover red flags, negotiable clauses, tenant rights, and how to prot...</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>

<style>
  .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
  .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
